The Real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the Exodus of the Israelites from Egypt led by Moses.
I grew up with that.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven from their bases in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government in the early 1930s.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and treacherous grasslands, with Mao guiding the column to victory after victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of perseverance, courage, and hope in the face of unbelievable hardships, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained—exhausted, terribly wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they counterattacked, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and established Mao's New China.
To what extent does China's founding myth hold up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, I set out to trace its footsteps.
It remains a terrifying journey through regions that have changed little to this day, still inaccessible and incredibly impoverished.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I managed to locate 40 of them and conducted interviews with them – they were ordinary people who had been left behind or had made it to the end, but their stories were extremely revealing.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, no bigger than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: his father had been arrested and would not be released until Huang agreed.
He thought of deserting, but stayed, fearing to be caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army of 86,000 had been reduced to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the army's first major engagement on the march.
Yet no more than 15,000 died in the battle; the rest disappeared.
Another battle, the Battle of the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. Allegedly, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of Nationalist troops guarding the Luding Bridge with machine guns, clearing the way for the marching forces.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of *Red Star Over China*, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event of the Long March, and it is still praised as such today.
Yet the documents I reviewed suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu initially told a completely different story to the party historians. "The matter wasn't as complicated as people later made it out to be," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should respect the truth."
"How they represent it is a different matter."
Thus the legend lives on.
There was merely a skirmish above the Dadu.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, allowed Mao to pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were going.
There were constant discussions about the final destination.
When they came together in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
Yet the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could scarcely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
Women were ordered to turn around and go back home because there was not enough food.
About a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the Party decided that the Long March had to continue.
Yet she saved Chiang Kai-shek's capture by the general whom Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
Not, however, for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's archrival, and had the task of seeking help from Russia across the western Chinese border.
Yet Mao sent them contradictory orders, so that they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the Red Army's greatest defeat.
Nevertheless, it is absent from official historical records.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his concubine.
That was enough for the Party to brand her a traitor and to deny all the years she had dedicated to the army.
They and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for a half-century to be recognized as participants of the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, despaired, and endured.
Hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom.
The executions continued until practically no officers were left to take command in the battles.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them through communist propaganda.
They endured their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other peoples.
They endured their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other peoples.
What drove her to do so?
I interviewed one of the top generals about what he knew of communism at the time. "I had no idea then, just as I have none now," he replied. "I even doubt whether Mao himself knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope for a just and progressive society.
Nobody perhaps – or could have known – how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice would be, and how enormous the difference between the dream and reality would turn out to be.
